    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Well-built fix for a real flake. The root-cause analysis is sharp: the deferred `conn.Close()` only ran after the 30s wait returned, so nothing unblocked the read within the window. Replacing the defer with explicit close at each exit point is the right correction, and `forceClose` keeps the new structure clean. Four unit tests cover four distinct `Close()` paths, timeouts are struct fields for deterministic testing, and the sentinel design keeps signal for genuine failures.\n\nSeverity count: 1 P3, 2 P4, 4 Nit.\n\nAs Bisky put it: \"Three are genuine gems, one is genuine, and one case never got cut.\"\n\nNotable observations from the panel (not posted inline):\n\n- The SSH close path (`closeFn` at conn.go:251) has the same stall vulnerability this PR fixes for RPTY: `<-time.After(connCloseTimeout)` with no force-close fallback. Noted by Knov and Mafu-san as informational; the PR is correctly scoped to PLAT-116.\n- If both `c.readErr` and `t.C` are ready in the graceful select (conn.go:159), Go picks randomly. Timer winning when the read already completed produces a false `errRPTYGracefulCloseTimeout`. Harmless because the sentinel is non-fatal, and the window is vanishingly narrow (Pariston).\n- `forceClose` discards the read error unconditionally. The error is also surfaced through the drain path in `run.go`, so information is not truly lost at the system level (Mafuuu, Meruem).\n- The graceful close path discards the `c.conn.Close()` error with `_ =` (conn.go:161). Consistent with `forceClose` and acceptable for a scale test utility where the connection is being torn down (Chopper).\n\n\n---\n\n`scaletest/workspacetraffic/conn.go:95-99`\n\n**P4** [CRF-3] `readErr` is only populated inside `Read()`. If no goroutine is calling `Read`, both the graceful wait and `forceClose` time out after 35s, producing misleading \"timeout waiting for read\" errors even though the connection was successfully closed underneath.\n\nCurrently satisfied by the runner's drain goroutine and the test's `startDrain`, but the contract is invisible at the type boundary. Since `rptyConn` is unexported and used in one place, the risk is bounded.\n\n> \"Anyone who reuses `rptyConn` in a new context will discover this as a 35s hang.\" *(Hisoka)*\n\nA doc comment on `newPTYConn` stating the caller must have an active Read loop for `Close` to complete would make the assumption visible. *(Meruem P4, Hisoka Note)*\n\n> \ud83e\udd16\n\n> \ud83e\udd16 This review was automatically generated with Coder Agents.\n",
